Dear MCSD Parents and Guardians,
Please remember - Effective Thursday, Sept. 10 at 3:25 p.m., all student learning model enrollments - whether fully-in person (grades PK-6), hybrid (grades 7-8) or fully-virtual - will be final for grades PK-8. The deadline for Marshalltown High School students to decide between hybrid learning or fully-virtual learning is Friday, Sept. 11 at 3:25 p.m.

We will not allow any PK-12 student to switch from his/her decision after the above deadlines. The only exception will be for families with NEW students to the District, who will be able to choose between fully-virtual learning and either fully in-person (grades PK-6) or hybrid (grades 7-12) learning.

STUDENTS AND FAMILIES USING EDGENUITY (Grades PK-5):
We are aware of ongoing issues with Edgenuity, and the program's company continues to work diligently to get the program back up and running.

We appreciate your patience and understanding as we work to create balanced classrooms and assign teachers to both in-person and virtual learners.

Please remember that face masks and/or face shields are required while on MCSD school property. This requirement extends to everyone who enters District buildings or grounds, including parents or guardians dropping off or picking up their child or children. The purpose of this requirement is to promote and protect health and safety during the coronavirus pandemic.
We appreciate your understanding. Thank you for helping Marshalltown Schools have a successful start to the school year!

EDGENUITY/EDMENTUM AND PK-5 WORKBOOKS
MCSD is currently aware of technical issues on the side of both of our online education vendors, Edmentum and Edgenuity. Both companies are working diligently to resolve the issues.
Students should be receiving login information to their district-provided email, but if it is not currently working, please be patient while those companies work through their issues. If your student(s) has/have not received a login, we will provide more information about how to receive the login in the near future.
PK-5 workbooks are now ready to pick up at the Central Office from 7: 30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Monday-Friday.
Thank you. We appreciate your patience!

post_text:
FREE MEALS UPDATE FROM MCSD:

Dear MCSD students and families,
Marshalltown Community School District will continue to serve free meals to children 18 years old and younger until further notice. The District Food Service Department is able to continue serving free meals to children due to an extension in funding from the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA).

While this funding remains available to MCSD, all school meals will be served for free to all Bobcat students 18 years old and younger, regardless of their learning model (fully in-person, fully-online, or hybrid).

If there is a change in the District's free meal programming, students and families will be notified immediately. If you have any questions regarding school meals, contact the MCSD Food Service Department at 641-754-1185.

MCSD TRANSPORTATION UPDATE:
The MCSD Transportation Department has been working diligently to ensure transportation to and from school is as safe and efficient as possible for Bobcat students.

Families whose children use District transportation services will receive an email message through the MCSD Transfinder program, as well as a mailed letter, with bus route information, pick-up and drop-off details, school bus safety expectations, and more. Those letters and messages are currently being sent and will arrive very soon.

If you have any questions regarding MCSD school transportation, please contact Transportation Director Rex Kozak at rkozak@marshalltown.k12.ia.us or 641-754-1195. For more information from the Transportation Department regarding the 2020-21 school year, visit https://www.marshalltown.k12.ia.us/media/cms/Districtwide_transportation_update__FEAE362D9C25B.pdf

post_text:
Hello MCSD Families,
We hope you are continuing to recover well from the Aug. 10 storm. See below for a District update for today, Monday, Aug. 24:

- All but two of the District's buildings are open to the public, with Woodbury Elementary School and the District Transportation Office still experiencing challenges with power and internet access.

- Woodbury Elementary staff will work to answer emails as much as possible. However, they will not be able to answer direct calls to Woodbury due to phone system issues, and will return voicemails when possible.

- The Transportation Office can be reached via email, but the phone system is currently down at that building.

We appreciate your patience as remaining power and internet issues are addressed at MCSD.

Hello Bobcat Families,

Our thoughts remain with you, and we hope you are safe and well. Here is an update as of 10:30 a.m. today, Friday, Aug. 21, on where we are as a District:

The following buildings are re-opened to the public:
- The District's Central Office
- Anson Elementary School
- Fisher Elementary School
- Hoglan Elementary School
- Rogers Elementary School
- Franklin Elementary School
- Lenihan Intermediate School
- Miller Middle School
- Marshalltown High School
- Marshalltown Learning Academy

Woodbury Elementary remains closed for now, and updates will be sent when they are able to reopen.

FREE MEALS FOR CHILDREN REMINDER: Free meals are being served to students younger than 18 on weekdays through Aug. 31. The meals are available from 11:30 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. at Miller Middle School, as well as at multiple mobile meal bus stops in Marshalltown. More details are available here: https://www.marshalltown.k12.ia.us/media/cms/Summer_Meals_resumes_message_73400640C9B07.pdf

post_text:
Update from City of Marshalltown - Local Government:

City of Marshalltown Media Announcement - Damage Assessments

The City of Marshalltown is conducting visual assessments of the damage to structures citywide this week. Staff will be classifying the damage level based on the FEMA damage ranking system. Properties that are identified as having major damage or a destroyed status may be subject to placarding by the City of Marshalltown. The notice will direct owners to contact the Building Official with a corrective plan of action which may include demolition or repair. We understand that many owners are still working with insurance adjusters in determining a plan of action, so it is important to communicate with the Housing & Community Development Department on the status of the property. Owners who do not respond by September 15, 2020 with a plan or have not secured the appropriate permits may be subject to further action. If your property is placarded please contact the Housing & Community Development Department at 641-754-5756.

post_text:
The social-emotional well-being of Bobcat students is a top priority of the Marshalltown Community School District. To provide students and families with information and resources on social-emotional well-being, we created the new Social-Emotional Learning (SEL) web page (https://bit.ly/3ee2TYX) on our district website.
The SEL page includes high-quality, accessible information on what social-emotional learning is and the strategies the district uses to address social-emotional health.
District resources - such as the five-part ‚ÄúSupporting Children & Families During School Closure‚Äù video series - are available on the SEL web page, as are resources from local partners and national organizations.

Wishing all Bobcats a safe, healthy, happy summer!

post_text:
The MCSD Summer Meals program starts Monday, June 8

Free meals to children 18 years old and younger will continue to be provided throughout the Marshalltown Community School District this summer.
The MCSD Summer Meals program kicks off Monday, June 8 and will run through Friday, July 31 (excluding July 3 at all sites). Meals will be served in the same manner as they have been during the last several weeks of the 2019-20 school year due to school closure - that includes nine school building sites and on mobile meal bus routes.
Food items may include sandwiches, cereal, graham crackers, muffins, fresh fruits and vegetables, and more. The district will also offer "Take and Bake" meals that can be picked up and then cooked at home.
All questions about the MCSD Summer Meals program should be directed to the MCSD Food Service Department at (641) 754-1000. Meal schedules for school sites and mobile routes are attached to this post. All of this information can also be found here: https://www.marshalltown.k12.ia.us/parents/2020-mcsd-summer-meals-program/

post_text:
Marshalltown Schools will close for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year
(For the full press release, follow this link: https://bit.ly/3cvnlU3 or see attached image)
In accordance with a mandate from Iowa Gov. Kim Reynolds, Marshalltown Community School District facilities will remain closed through the end of the current school year, including all extracurricular activities and events. The last day of school for students is set for Thursday, June 4, 2020. Monday, June 8, 2020 will be the last work day for teachers. MCSD administrators, teachers and staff are working with the Iowa Department of Education on continuing to provide voluntary learning from home during the closure. Staff and students will have the ability to collect personal items from district facilities; the exact schedule and manner for that to take place will be developed and released in the near future.

post_text: Thank you to all of our hard-working Food Service and Transportation employees for ensuring as many families as possible have meals to eat during the week, as well as over the weekend!
shared_text:
Marshalltown School Nutrition Services
March 27 at 3:47 PM ¬∑

The Marshalltown Nutrition And Transportation Departments worked hard today to prepare meals for students over the weekend. We are completely happy and fulfilled that we are able to continue to feed and deliver meals to students while school is closed.

We are so proud of the Nutrition and Transportation staff for coming together to make this possible! Beyond grateful for the team we have!

Stay well everyone and enjoy your weekend!

We anticipate minimal contact between staff and students. The health of our employee's and the community are top priority as we strive to meet the needs of children in our community.

post_text:
Good news for anyone who missed the recent poinsettias fundraiser!
The Marshalltown High School Botany Club will be selling 6-inch ($10) and 4-inch ($7) poinsettias in a variety of colors from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m. Saturday, Dec. 7 at the Winter Holiday Craft Show at the Marshall County Fairgrounds, 1308 E. Olive St. The show is free to attend.
In order to guarantee that we have the size and color you want, please pre-order by making a payment to Cindy Braack at the MHS office (641-754-1130) and emailing to confirm we have received the order.
This second set of poinsettia orders will NOT be delivered, but buyers can pick them up at the Craft Show any time from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m. Saturday.
Thank you!
